commit_message:
Set verbosity by default for memcached

This sets of one level of verbosity for memcached by default. This
allows us to see any errors or warnings in the logs.

Change-Id: Icc6f56c9e0ee6100286d07c8b6660a08baabb241
Related-Bug: #1720183
(cherry picked from commit 15ad21ba08e92b302318bdc34112601ce666ff35)

[{'created': '2017-10-30 12:55:49.000000000', 'message': "persist memcached logs in /var/log/containers/memcached/memcached.log

We used to bind-mount /var/log/memcached.log, but this resulted in the
file being createdin the memcached container as a directory, since this
file didn't exist.

This commit takes the approach of other containers and gets the logs to
a memcached directory in /var/log/containers.

Change-Id: I926b65fa557ad56b4faa2be34452b58f7b01247a

commit_message:
persist memcached logs in /var/log/containers/memcached/memcached.log

We used to bind-mount /var/log/memcached.log, but this resulted in the
file being createdin the memcached container as a directory, since this
file didn't exist.

This commit takes the approach of other containers and gets the logs to
a memcached directory in /var/log/containers.

Change-Id: I926b65fa557ad56b4faa2be34452b58f7b01247a
Closes-Bug: #1720183
(cherry picked from commit 5020f38301a9a0a70f34878196250e24fc639dec)

commit_message:
Fix python 3.x portability issue

cmp() as well as sorted(.., cmp=) does not exist in Python 3.x
anymore. Convert to using sorted(..., key=) instead, which
exists both in Python 2.x and Python 3.x. This isn't caught
in CI because the code is entirely unused.

Change-Id: I44a53291199c77d46c15beeff30b3c186f16cc64

commit_message:
Do not return the config download path but only print it

Returning the config download path is wrong because its return
a wrong RC to the cli
We just have to print the path to the console

Change-Id: Ic633361c144964722099774d85006394b44b4d9d
(cherry picked from commit 8b071e55fca947810200aa1542eb13a6e1441563)

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Move log collection to 'post' stage""

This reverts commit af3a08a5b1f14e61957f5f84c5dfdab2ddfb7279
but adds the tests repository as a required repo to make sure that
it works properly across other repositories. This will be tested
through another review using depends-on so that it does not
break the role tests again.

Change-Id: If9bded9d60e2fe839c0ec8c49cc5102b5a541474
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Use new zuul v3 git src location

Previously we used a complex job definition to make sure
that the appropriate git clones for cross-repo testing
were in place. Now we just used the same location where
zuul v3 puts the git sources automatically when a
cross-repo test is done.

This ensures that our cross-repo tests do what they're
supposed to and that we're using the same default location
as the rest of openstack's tests, making it more intuitive.

Change-Id: Ia5ab6aa43f912b3cb4adf98154cd3da12688c2e0
(cherry picked from commit b631d90dd514847aee7a1719192a479ec4440464)

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

Change-Id: I9a6d2d0c844ef17995cb7451f2ad7895374292ea

[{'created': '2017-10-30 14:33:36.000000000', 'message': 'Restrict legacy-tempest-dsvm-nova-wsgi-full to stable/ocata

NOVA_USE_MOD_WSGI=True is the default in devstack since Pike,
see change If2d7e363a6541854f2e30c03171bef7a41aff745.

Therefore we can restrict the nova-wsgi-full job to just running
against stable/ocata patches.

stable/newton is intentionally left out since newton is soon to
be EOL.

Change-Id: I0d69110b466e6c82167c0ccd93b481bde6069b8f
'}]
commit_message:
Restrict legacy-tempest-dsvm-nova-wsgi-full to stable/ocata

NOVA_USE_MOD_WSGI=True is the default in devstack since Pike,
see change If2d7e363a6541854f2e30c03171bef7a41aff745.

Therefore we can restrict the nova-wsgi-full job to just running
against stable/ocata patches.

stable/newton is intentionally left out since newton is soon to
be EOL.

Change-Id: I0d69110b466e6c82167c0ccd93b481bde6069b8f

commit_message:
rp: break functions out of _set_traits()

Breaks functions out of the _set_traits() function for deleting and
adding a set of trait identifiers to a resource provider. In the
process, reworks the _set_traits() function to just operate on internal
identifiers and not string names.

blueprint: de-orm-resource-providers

Change-Id: I5b448c3e9b5f7a259488dacabba093ea5a150298

commit_message:
Bypass web server during service setup

When connecting directly to a keystone host during service setup, use
the UWSGI ports instead of going through the web server to avoid any
potential errors with differing URI protocols or SSL certs not including
the hostnames of individual hosts.

mod_wsgi was the default deployment pre-Pike so that configuration will
still need to be catered for. A release note has been included for those
effected by the bug.

 Conflicts:
	tasks/keystone_service_setup.yml

Change-Id: Ie5b33f9d0210a23badb63cab72c481b027790be3
Closes-Bug: 1699191
(cherry picked from commit cabd7e9cef8c35df08958677892a82551b210c97)

commit_message:
Bypass web server during service setup

When connecting directly to a keystone host during service setup, use
the UWSGI ports instead of going through the web server to avoid any
potential errors with differing URI protocols or SSL certs not including
the hostnames of individual hosts.

mod_wsgi was the default deployment pre-Pike so that configuration will
still need to be catered for. A release note has been included for those
effected by the bug.

 Conflicts:
	tasks/keystone_service_setup.yml

Change-Id: Ie5b33f9d0210a23badb63cab72c481b027790be3
Closes-Bug: 1699191
(cherry picked from commit cabd7e9cef8c35df08958677892a82551b210c97)

commit_message:
use context mgr in instance.delete

Previous patch introduced a context manager to send instance.delete
notifications. This patch further spreads the usage of this context
manager.

Based on the review discussion soft delete notification emitted from
the compute/api is missleading as those are not really soft delete
cases. The only real soft delete case is when
compute.manager.soft_delete_instance() is called. So this patch also
changes the event type accordingly.

commit_message:
tests: replace .testr.conf with .stestr.conf

TrivialFix:In the change[1] os_testr changed under the covers
from using testr to stestr, so that we now get the following
warning:
   ostestr.py:120:
   UserWarning: No .stestr.conf file found in the CWD.
   Please create one to to replace the .testr.conf. You
   can find a script to do this in the stestr git repository.
So remove the .testr.conf and add .stestr.conf which was
generated using a utility script as documented here [2].
[1] Id7cb2a39a8308f1413608dcf19273a1d7f33592e
[2] https://media.readthedocs.org/pdf/stestr/stable/stestr.pdf

Change-Id: I4810ac86aeca23e5abff3dc0417ffa3aa2f3a199

commit_message:
Add python3 support

Not all projects support python3 yet (swift being the worst offender)
and some only have partial support. Nova doesnt support python3 with xen
yet, but it does for everything else.

With this patch a full python3 deploy of openstack *should* be possible.
For now, at least it all builds.

Change-Id: Id03bbae1063b21e949085a3ef8f8c7534d2db3ff

commit_message:
Image create v1/v2 compatible in compute test_images_rbac

This is due to glance v1 not accepting the kwarg ``name``, thus on
systems with both a v1 and v2 endpoint configured, setUpClass will
fail.

Co-Authored-By: Felipe Monteiro <felipe.monteiro@att.com>
Change-Id: I636e8a72210524840917e147e125ed52ed390bbe

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-15 01:49:41.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Only save compiled wheels

With this patch we stop trying to collect all possible packages we would
want and instead only save packages that we needed to build into wheels
outselves.

Doing it this way has a few advantages:
  * Reduced layer size to 100MB wheels from 250MB wheels
  * Can install additional packages that were not built into the wheels
image ahead of time (assuming they exist as wheels upstream)
  * Faster build times
  * Less I/O when building

However, currently we are in a unique spot where we do not reach
upstream for anything beyond apt/yum packages. So we don't currently
reach out to PyPI when installing anything. This makes it a touch harder
to build in an air-gapped environment. That said, you would already need
a PyPI mirror to build in an air-gapped environment to build the
requirements image in the first place, so there are no new complications
to the situation.

Change-Id: I746d315ff642c951bbe798af7fbf951b5aa81a4f
"}, {'created': '2017-10-15 02:04:16.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Only save compiled wheels

However, currently we are in a unique spot where we do not reach

Change-Id: I746d315ff642c951bbe798af7fbf951b5aa81a4f
"}, {'created': '2017-10-19 22:40:46.000000000', 'message': 'Only save compiled wheels

With this patch we stop trying to collect all possible packages we would
want and instead only save packages that we needed to build into wheels
ourselves because they were only distrubuted as source tarballs upstream

Doing it this way has a few advantages:
  * Reduced layer size to 50MB wheels from 250MB wheels
  * Can install additional packages that were not built into the wheels
image ahead of time (assuming they exist as wheels upstream)
  * Faster build times on slower WAN connections
  * Less I/O when building

This has no affect on building in an air-gapped environment. You would
already need a PyPI mirror to build in an air-gapped environment in the
first place.

Change-Id: I746d315ff642c951bbe798af7fbf951b5aa81a4f
'}, {'created': '2017-10-20 01:42:20.000000000', 'message': 'Only save compiled wheels

With this patch we stop trying to collect all possible packages we would
want and instead only save packages that we needed to build into wheels
ourselves because they were only distrubuted as source tarballs upstream

Doing it this way has a few advantages:
  * Reduced layer size to 50MB wheels from 250MB wheels
  * Can install additional packages that were not built into the wheels
image ahead of time (assuming they exist as wheels upstream)
  * Faster build times on slower WAN connections
  * Less I/O when building

We explicitly limit to binary installs with "--only-binary :all:" to
prevent any accidental source building.

This has no affect on building in an air-gapped environment. You would
already need a PyPI mirror to build in an air-gapped environment in the
first place.

Change-Id: I746d315ff642c951bbe798af7fbf951b5aa81a4f

commit_message:
Only save compiled wheels

With this patch we stop trying to collect all possible packages we would
want and instead only save packages that we needed to build into wheels
ourselves because they were only distrubuted as source tarballs upstream

Doing it this way has a few advantages:
  * Reduced layer size to 50MB wheels from 250MB wheels
  * Can install additional packages that were not built into the wheels
image ahead of time (assuming they exist as wheels upstream)
  * Faster build times on slower WAN connections
  * Less I/O when building

We explicitly limit to binary installs with "--only-binary :all:" to
prevent any accidental source building.

This has no affect on building in an air-gapped environment. You would
already need a PyPI mirror to build in an air-gapped environment in the
first place.

Change-Id: I746d315ff642c951bbe798af7fbf951b5aa81a4f

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-09-28 18:55:29.000000000', 'message': "Fix live migration grenade ceph setup

Grenade runs in singleconductor mode for queens
as of change:

  If4c82ca12fe7b8b1ca7cfd8181d24dbd8dad3baa

However, the nova configuration during ceph setup
was using NOVA_CPU_CONF which is /etc/nova/nova-cpu.conf,
which is not what we want when configuring nova.conf
for the compute service in singleconductor mode.

Devstack has similar logic for stuff like this, so
we just have to handle it here since we're in a special
snowflake.

The stable/queens systemd stuff is all removed too since
we run with systemd on the old pike side and can restart
services properly with systemd on the new queens side
during grenade live migration CI job runs.

Change-Id: Iccb8eb55a5cc2a3d08e7fd6e31c89b3b5f8d0c70
Closes-Bug: #1720191

commit_message:
Fix live migration grenade ceph setup

Grenade runs in singleconductor mode for queens
as of change:

  If4c82ca12fe7b8b1ca7cfd8181d24dbd8dad3baa

However, the nova configuration during ceph setup
was using NOVA_CPU_CONF which is /etc/nova/nova-cpu.conf,
which is not what we want when configuring nova.conf
for the compute service in singleconductor mode.

Devstack has similar logic for stuff like this, so
we just have to handle it here since we're in a special
snowflake.

The stable/queens systemd stuff is all removed too since
we run with systemd on the old pike side and can restart
services properly with systemd on the new queens side
during grenade live migration CI job runs.

Change-Id: Iccb8eb55a5cc2a3d08e7fd6e31c89b3b5f8d0c70

commit_message:
[tools]  Add a tool to make a no-op change

I used something like this when testing reno 2.5.0.  It's clearly a work
in progress but I figure we could all fix/test it rather than me having
another half implemented tool

Change-Id: I2fa844f4cf8dd7e5c06461b7f7926a7cf84515c3

commit_message:
Filter duplicated RTs in compiled list

The code does not filter duplicates: e.g. an RT that is both
in route_targets and import_targets will be present twice in the
RPCs between neutron server and agents, and agents will also pass
this RT twice to bagpipe-bgp.

This patch fix avoid duplicated RTs in compiled Import Targets and
Export Targets lists.

Change-Id: Ia5b76235c75f005e3c53f7cddc8e085376f5ebe1
Closes-Bug: 1719589

commit_message:
Update zuul jobs with the per branch data

Following the advise of jeblair, we should be moving all our jobs
directly in-tree, per branch, to avoid current bugs.
On top of that, it improves reliability and maintenance over time.

We do not need branch matchers anymore in that case.

Change-Id: I49cfd8716ac02c80dad1e409a43b3ff279f37ce9

commit_message:
Remove instruction to append DockerInsecureRegistryAddress

This is now done automatically by the prepare command that detects if
the registry is secure and appends DockerInsecureRegistryAddress when
needed.

Change-Id: I0c34cc86703888089b20e90accef9ab2c417bf8a
Depends-On: I74586145c222921880402cec92bbaa5f10e8b972
Related-Bug: #1722632

commit_message:
Add release highlights

This adds the ability to provide release highlights in the deliverable
yaml file. These highlights can then be extracted and displayed into
published documentation using a new 'cycle-highlights' directive.

Change-Id: I40791dad4b5a4d2c4089e5e43d52f00b52cc3217

(10 comments)

Looking pretty shiny!

There's a bunch of annoying fallout from making the default lock file named '.lock-0' instead of just '.lock' - it reminded me a lot of storage policies... what do you think about:

https://gist.github.com/clayg/945f3d0dd9c198a8726def6d251c87a0

It is maybe a small thing, but there is actually a small race with our lock pattern where two processes can actually both create the file `.lock` with different fd's [1] that only exists the first time a name is created (once .lock exists the code doesn't have that race) - but so there is actually some (small?) utilitarian benefit of keeping the name of the default lock file consistent through upgrade - it's not *purely* ascetic!

I'm worried about not having test coverage on the legacy configuration option - maybe the thought is we want to remove it later so save us the trouble of removing the tests - but I feel like the extra burden of doing a bunch of manual validation now and then trying to be careful not to break it until we're ready to rip it out pales compared the small cost of writing/keeping a couple of unitests around to hit/cover/assert the legacy configuration case.  Ain't nobody trying to break legacy configs!  Let's not break by the power of testing on purpose!

1. you could reopen and test samefile but ain't no body got time for that https://docs.python.org/2/library/os.path.html#os.path.sameopenfile"}, {'account_id': 13852, 'date': '2017-03-08 21:39:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 13852, 'date': '2017-03-08 21:41:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

As near as I can tell, you're absolutely correct [1].  In retrospect I think I had conflated a past defeat trying to create a similar lock context manager that tried to cleanup the lock file when it was done with it.  The failure there was probably when a second process that was blocked on the flock while the first process released its lock and cleaned up the lock file - which opened the door for a third process to create a new file and take a second concurrent lock on that.  The race was on *re*create.  I think somewhere along the line I ran into O_EXCEL and convinced myself of something that wasn't there.  A million thanks for calling me out and pushing me to correct my misconceptions!

So the use of the storage policy naming convention is *purely* ascetic!  ;)

I'll take a fresh look at this as soon as I can.  Thanks again.

commit_message:
Replace replication_one_per_device by custom count

This commit replaces boolean replication_one_per_device by an integer
replication_concurrency_per_device. The new configuration parameter is
passed to utils.lock_path() which now accept as an argument a limit for
the number of locks that can be acquired for a specific path.

Instead of trying to lock path/.lock, utils.lock_path() now tries to lock
files path/.lock-X, where X is in the range (0, N), N being the limit for
the number of locks allowed for the path. The default value of limit is
set to 1.

Change-Id: I3c3193344c7a57a8a4fc7932d1b10e702efd3572

commit_message:
Pass the correct image to build_request_spec in conductor.rebuild_instance

If we're calling build_request_spec in conductor.rebuild_instance,
it's because we are evacuating and the instance is so old it does
not have a request spec. We need the request_spec to pass to the
scheduler to pick a destination host for the evacuation.

For evacuate, nova-api does not pass any image reference parameters,
and even if it did, those are image IDs, not an image meta dict that
build_request_spec expects, so this code has just always been wrong.

This change fixes the problem by passing a primitive version of
the instance.image_meta which build_request_spec will then return
back to conductor and that gets used to build a RequestSpec object
from primitives.

It's important to use the correct image meta so that the scheduler
can properly filter hosts using things like the
AggregateImagePropertiesIsolation and ImagePropertiesFilter filters.

Change-Id: I0c8ce65016287de7be921c312493667a8c7f762e
Closes-Bug: #1727855

commit_message:
Add NULL check before passing to in_() column operator

In some cases we may need to pass key=None filters to get_object()
and get_objects() methods, however we lack of NULL check before these
filters reach in_(), which will not return any matching queries in db
layer.

We need to do manual equals matches if NULL element exists in filters,
instead of pass them to in_() operator.

Change-Id: I7980b82e2627b7b097cae0a714d22e680cddd340
Closes-Bug: #1724177

commit_message:
Remove Gerrit contact info filing step

This feature is no longer supported by the version of Gerrit that we
run. The decision was made to drop the need for contact filing because
the openstack.org website has an api now to do member lookups and we
don't have to rely on CLA signing in Gerrit for technical election
eligibility.

This coupled with Gerrit dropping support for the feature means we just
don't do it anymore.

Change-Id: I28bee0b5a8e8ed53fedd2369de54504369f5032f

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-30 16:24:28.000000000', 'message': "Fix issue with different decimal separators

An issue was discovered in the ZFSonLinux driver wherein on a system
set to have a locale where the decimal separator is not a period but
rather a comma the method translate_string_size_to_float() would fail
because it's regex to find sizes in strings did not account for any
other decimal separators other than periods.

This fix updates the regular expression to accept either a period or
a comma as a decimal separator in a size string.

Many thanks to Dr. Clemens Hardewig for reporting the original bug
and providing an updated regular expression.

Change-Id: I15da4aaff90814eed03816db013d6acc89ba2ee8
Closes-Bug: #1714691
(cherry picked from commit 8800e54f770c4c4a6f813a5ea72bb12316482d87)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix issue with different decimal separators

An issue was discovered in the ZFSonLinux driver wherein on a system
set to have a locale where the decimal separator is not a period but
rather a comma the method translate_string_size_to_float() would fail
because it's regex to find sizes in strings did not account for any
other decimal separators other than periods.

This fix updates the regular expression to accept either a period or
a comma as a decimal separator in a size string.

Many thanks to Dr. Clemens Hardewig for reporting the original bug
and providing an updated regular expression.

Change-Id: I15da4aaff90814eed03816db013d6acc89ba2ee8
Closes-Bug: #1714691
(cherry picked from commit 8800e54f770c4c4a6f813a5ea72bb12316482d87)

commit_message:
Enable longer Keystone token life

The devstack plugin sets a 3 hour Keystone token life
but Keystone is already running when this configuration change
is called so Keystone still runs with the default for the tests.

Add a restart of Keystone to enable the longer life.

Change-Id: Ie340b1c0b56652fc9ca4c0981468363c1be9fb25

commit_message:
[reno] Update ironic-dbsync's check object version

This updates the release note pertaining to ironic-dbsync's
check of the object versions, to be explicit that these are the
database records that correspond to the IronicObjects.

This is a follow up to 6a91b38ca48eea2892a5a82b4369f1f9b277d019.

Change-Id: I1e2b3dc60529551746a0c7a258e5ce3cf509f59f

commit_message:
Fix exception handling in journal

A change [1] introduced a bug that broke the exception handling due to
passing incorrect arguments to the code handling them. This patch
fixes the issue and adds unit tests to catch this in the future.

[1]: I31085cf73618df48f55f3169e071d2cb64c9b018

Change-Id: I22cbe8d46e10a5d53bc570b2547dd72ca6865989
Closes-Bug: #1728534

commit_message:
Dynamically determine SSL version in unit tests

KMIP by default tries to use PROTOCOL_TLSv1_2, but not all systems that
run the unit tests necessarily have this.

Dynamically determine the version to use.

Change-Id: Ia13841b3547332d6d5044b446b073dc2394bb8fb

commit_message:
Move ironic legacy jobs into the ironic tree

This patch moves the legacy ironic CI jobs into the ironic tree instead
of storing them in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs to give us
control as we migrate the legacy jobs to the new ansible roles.

This also removes branch specifics from project.yaml, leaving only the
jobs we need to run on current release.

Change-Id: Ib728fadbdab2eb9f1ba5112297a32dbdbfd1d5fd
(cherry picked from commit 4b37c29b5e180d68e744e8114e2f414023d1376a)

commit_message:
Auto-generate sample config file

This PS auto-generates the sample config file using
oslo-config-generator which is how every project should reliably
produce a config file.

In addition, the Patrole documentation was updated to link to the
generated config file, so that the documentation accurately
shows config options.

Change-Id: Ib3c39084b4c2b5a0078d1293d882cf9a9050b29b
Closes-Bug: #1709490

project to take effect.

commit_message:
do not run the py35 job for deliverable file changes

Only the releases repo has deliverable files, but it seems excessive
to duplicate the job definition just to ignore those files.

Change-Id: I06dcc292655c13c5eaa777cd9d1df7743ee2de9e
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
rp: remove _HasAResourceProvider mixin

The _HasAResourceProvider mixin is no longer needed since the results
of AllocationList.get_all_by_XXX() and InventoryList.get_all_by_XXX()
have been modified to manually construct the Allocation and Inventory
POD objects using optimized non-ORM queries, so removing the mixin.

blueprint: de-orm-resource-providers

Change-Id: I1cc50c2e2501fef1fe8bad8451f833380371def8

commit_message:
Change QoS configuration manual

As [1] shows, the controller node hosts the Neutron server but
also agents like L3 and DHCP which require also OVS or LinuxBridge
agent to be running on it.
To enable QoS is required to enable the 'service_plugins' and
the 'extension_drivers', along with the agent section in the plugin
config if the agent is running on this host.

In the network node and the compute node only the agent
'extensions' configuration is needed to enable QoS
on the agent.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/security-guide/networking/architecture.html

Closes-Bug: #1720077

Change-Id: I14128aabe0a9209c31a1bd4c76eed1182364ccdf
Co-Authored-By: Slawek Kaplonski <slawek@kaplonski.pl>

commit_message:
Bump MAX version of client to 3.45

Adding a shared_targets field to Volumes in Cinder.  This doesn't
require any changes in the client, however we do need to bump the
MAX MV support value.

Show volumes now returns two new fields that will be displayed in
the show command:
    shared_targets: <True|False>
    backend_name:  <backend-name-of-storage-device>

Change-Id: Ie1291f90756c3752de562f022126af2f6b3e0637

commit_message:
Autodetect insecure registry in container image prepare

This change automatically inserts the DockerInsecureRegistryAddress
parameter into the containers image environment file if the registry
is reachable and unencrypted.

This eliminates a documented manual step, which is also required
throughout CI. It has been done in tripleoclient so that it can be
backported. The dedicated workflow for
blueprint container-prepare-workflow will have its own insecure
detection.

Change-Id: I74586145c222921880402cec92bbaa5f10e8b972
Closes-Bug: #1722632

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

Change-Id: Ie8a6610bb44ad41379d39e35e21d946d2dff820f

commit_message:
Tripleo PTP (Precision Time Protocol) support

This spec introduces support for a time synchronization
method called PTP (defined in the IEEE 1588-2008) which
provides better time accuracy than NTP in general. With
hardware timestamping support on the host, PTP can
achieve clock accuracy in the sub-microsecond range,
making it suitable for measurement and control systems.

Change-Id: I3e5cc2e854eb8e0374e36640816dcdb5fc8a773f

commit_message:

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code

commit_message:
Fixes vhostuser port prefix with ODL OVS host config

The incorrect prefix of 'vhu_' was being used for vhost user ports and
it should be simply 'vhu'.

Closes-Bug: 1722917

Change-Id: I960f85845ca5c99aa14a3291b8eea10806081624
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 384967bb5d4e30aa4d0cb4f5de3f458d52ab64e0)

commit_message:
Using --option ARGUMENT

The OpenStack CLI commands support both --option ARGUMENT and --option=ARGUMENT.
In technical publications, use --option ARGUMENT.[1]

[1]https://docs.openstack.org/doc-contrib-guide/writing-style/code-conventions.html

Change-Id: Ib22d435d04c9bbc9369fdb5364742d02f65b61e8

set to have a locale where the decimal separator is not a period but

commit_message:
Fix issue with different decimal separators

An issue was discovered in the ZFSonLinux driver wherein on a system
set to have a locale where the decimal separator is not a period but
rather a comma the method translate_string_size_to_float() would fail
because it's regex to find sizes in strings did not account for any
other decimal separators other than periods.

This fix updates the regular expression to accept either a period or
a comma as a decimal separator in a size string.

Many thanks to Dr. Clemens Hardewig for reporting the original bug
and providing an updated regular expression.

Change-Id: I15da4aaff90814eed03816db013d6acc89ba2ee8
Closes-Bug: #1714691

commit_message:
shim RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTE_MAP from neutron-lib

neutron-lib now contains the rehomed API attributes.
As the usage of RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTE_MAP is fairly wide-spread
[1] this patch shims neutron's attribute map to use lib's allowing
consumers to move to lib's map without worry of syncing with this patch.
A subsequent patch will move neutron over to lib's attribute map.
Once consumers have moved over to lib for the RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTE_MAP
we can come back and remove the shim herein.

NeutronLibImpact

[1] http://codesearch.openstack.org/?q=%5C.RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTE_MAP

Change-Id: If0c010e9910d1256417162a059d1fdace31c290a

commit_message:
use RESOURCES from neutron-lib

Patch If0c010e9910d1256417162a059d1fdace31c290a already shimmed neutron
for using neutron-lib RESOURCES map. This patch builds upon the shim
and replaces all neutron's uses of RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTE_MAP with
neutron-lib's RESOURCES map.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I33bcd4a88083ca97941b60dbf59309e121dff1a1

commit_message:
Reference architecture: common bits

This change introduces the layout of the future reference architecture
guide. It also introduces common ideas and considerations, to avoid
repeating them for each provided architecture.

Change-Id: Icc56cdfc1c97a2bb0674a9a397259cecc0a08514

commit_message:
ironic-dbsync: check object versions

Now that we have rolling upgrades and the version column was
added and populated in the Pike release, we can add checks to
make sure the versions of objects in the DB are compatible
with this ironic release, before ironic-dbsync's upgrade or
online_data_migrations does its work. These ironic-dbsync
calls are made as part of upgrading to this (Queens) release.

Change-Id: I68758f8a29d483f5c0a7439fa2ea2962b2eb4124
Partial-Bug: #1708243

commit_message:
Clean up jinja2 templates on conditional checks

Starting in Ansible 2.3, jinja2 templates with conditionals were
no longer supported. Users should have always directly stated the
variables and not treated it as a string of jinja2 text to be
expanded.

In order to support newer ansible versions, the conditionals have
been updated accordingly.

Change-Id: Ib74c1783241436258dc0bd52a8a6990c00785775

Can we please just fix up the three containers (rabbit, galera, redis)? It took ages to merge this and the whole HA control plane is broken without this review.'}, {'account_id': 20172, 'date': '2017-10-06 12:51:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Can we please just fix up the three containers (rabbit, galera,
 > redis)? It took ages to merge this and the whole HA control plane
 > is broken without this review.

I.e. can't we just update pacemaker and resource-agents packages for those three containers as we did for the hosts?"}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2017-10-06 12:59:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

manually monkeying with containers is not really an ideal long term solution. We need a set of containers to all pass CI together as we have for packages. If we start pulling random containers from different sources, it becomes impossible to actually track what content is actually there.

I said on the bug that I would be fine with that for this special case, especially given that the automatic promote of containers is not even fully ready yet.

I put up this revert to have all the bases covered while we discuss what to do though.'}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2017-10-06 13:00:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

also, the fact that this would not have been passing CI if any CI that actually tested it on containers ran on it, makes me really lean towards revert being correct.'}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2017-10-06 13:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 20172, 'date': '2017-10-06 13:14:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> manually monkeying with containers is not really an ideal long term
 > solution. We need a set of containers to all pass CI together as we
 > have for packages. If we start pulling random containers from
 > different sources, it becomes impossible to actually track what
 > content is actually there.
 > 
 > I said on the bug that I would be fine with that for this special
 > case, especially given that the automatic promote of containers is
 > not even fully ready yet.

Aye. Which is why I was asking to fix up those packages in those three containers only.
Somehow I presumed (wrongly) that the new packages that we put in the pike repos for the hosts
would be picked up automagically.

 > I put up this revert to have all the bases covered while we discuss
 > what to do though.

I think fixing up the containers is the more low-impact approach, but if you guys
are vehemently against it, so be it.

If we really want to revert this one, I would need an ETA for the fixed up containers.
I.e. the HA plane is currently in a non really usable state without this change (barring
deployment coming up, anything else is probably just broken: controller reboot, restarts, etc)
And I also need to backport this to pike as well.

> also, the fact that this would not have been passing CI if any CI that actually tested it on containers ran on it, makes me really lean towards revert being correct.
We have been working with this change applied for the last months. It does work a lot better than what we currently have ;)'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2017-10-06 14:22:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2017-10-06 14:37:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2017-10-06 14:37:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Workflow'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-10-06 14:53:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Revert "Set meta container-attribute-target=host attribute"

This patch broke the containers scenario004 test because it relies on a
newer mariadb container than has actually passed CI at this time.

To revert this revert, we need to make sure we test
scenario004-containers against that patch.

This reverts commit 6bcb011723ad7b75f18914c887dc4fa4bad4d620.

Closes-Bug: 1721497

Change-Id: I34c7c388eed94db1735c45e26661a0af8cdce8e9

Due to Python's GIL [1], we can't use multiple threads for running
OpenStack services without a performance penalty, since the execution
ends up serialized, which defeats the purpose.

Instead, we should use several processes, since this approach doesn't

"}]
commit_message:
apache wsgi: Exchange defaults for workers and threads

Due to Python's GIL [1], we can't use multiple threads for running
OpenStack services without a performance penalty, since the execution
ends up serialized, which defeats the purpose.

Instead, we should use several processes, since this approach doesn't
have this limitation.

[1] https://wiki.python.org/moin/GlobalInterpreterLock

Change-Id: I2e07baf0cb99980a4207ca73204d242e9913f44c

commit_message:
Move pip_install deployment

This patch adds the pip_install role deployment into it's own
playbook. This will allow us to remove the meta-dependency for
the pip_install role in many of the independent role
repositories. That should save time in the gate and for
deployers.

Change-Id: Ic207dd1166088177fcee03d6b1729350884d1d7c
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
[Bug-Fix] Update VNFFG leaves db in error state

Currently in tacker there is no support for updating a chain or
a classifier. So if anyone was trying to update a chain through
the vnffg-update command of the tackerclient a NotImplementedError
was raising and that was leaving the whole tacker ecosystem in an error
state.

That was happening because some objects in the database was in an status
ERROR and some other in a status PENDING_UPDATE.

With this patch we are setting all the objects in the database in a
ERROR status therefore the user can delete the failed VNFFG without
erasing the whole tacker database.

Closes-Bug: #1724809

Change-Id: I2c399a33055ccce41be941eca0bee52508399fd7
Signed-off-by: Dimitrios Markou <mardim@intracom-telecom.com>

Fix beaker tests to use openstack_integration for RabbitMQ

The RabbitMQ acceptance tests used to be pointing towards the Kilo
repos.  This patch addresses it so that it leverages the Puppet
OpenStack integration manifests instead.

commit_message:
Fix endpoint examples in api-ref

Endpoints have no name property[1] so specifying one in an update
request is incorrect, nor should we expect one in response to a create.

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone/tree/keystone/catalog/schema.py?h=12.0.0#n90

Change-Id: I94ae15ef77872523920ed0b43fe5e09755766fb5

commit_message:
Consolidate V2Controller functionality

Since ec2 is the only use-case left for using the V2Controller,
we can consolidate what is left into two v3_to_v2 functions.
These can be removed once ec2 functionality is removed.

Change-Id: I3a4731738efe934238e38567a3c2cf514a3d7f23

This patchset was cherry picked to branch master as commit 49511e33c11a82f4381a2ac1616da087733b1404'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2017-10-30 14:33:14.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-27 05:09:23.000000000', 'message': "Resolve deployment issues with multi-node swift

Swift fails to deploy when using >1 storage node. The fact `need_sync`
was being set using information from ansible_local in an effort to
support rolling uprades sometime in the future. Sadly this variable
causes storage nodes to be removed from the key sync which results in a
failed build.  The task to define the `need_sync` fact has been
commented out and noted. If we decide serialized rolling uprades are
required for swift we can revisit this however until then we need to
remove this constraint and ensure we're allowing successfule deployments
and upgrades of swift.

Change-Id: Ia8697285baa714ab345381b28574a222c5881954
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Resolve deployment issues with multi-node swift

Swift fails to deploy when using >1 storage node. The fact `need_sync`
was being set using information from ansible_local in an effort to
support rolling uprades sometime in the future. Sadly this variable
causes storage nodes to be removed from the key sync which results in a
failed build.  The task to define the `need_sync` fact has been
commented out and noted. If we decide serialized rolling uprades are
required for swift we can revisit this however until then we need to
remove this constraint and ensure we're allowing successfule deployments
and upgrades of swift.

Change-Id: Ia8697285baa714ab345381b28574a222c5881954
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

subject: Don't run sync in upgrades

commit_message:
Don't run sync in upgrades

When running a rolling upgrade, each swift node is addressed
individually. This can result in undefined variables when a node doesn't
have the necessary SSH and ring information.

For minor upgrades, these changes are not necessary. They are only
necessary in fresh installs, or modifying storage capacity. Thus, this
patch checks to see if it's a new install (no swift venv_tag previously
defined) or it's the same version (current venv tag matches the previous
one) and only does syncs in those cases.

Change-Id: Ice3b4526609f5a5fd4472c8408de9ed08aea29e6

[{'created': '2017-10-27 14:25:02.000000000', 'message': "Resolve deployment issues with multi-node swift

Swift fails to deploy when using >1 storage node. The fact `need_sync`
was being set using information from ansible_local in an effort to
support rolling uprades sometime in the future. Sadly this variable
causes storage nodes to be removed from the key sync which results in a
failed build.  The task to define the `need_sync` fact has been
commented out and noted. If we decide serialized rolling uprades are
required for swift we can revisit this however until then we need to
remove this constraint and ensure we're allowing successfule deployments
and upgrades of swift.

commit_message:
Resolve deployment issues with multi-node swift

Swift fails to deploy when using >1 storage node. The fact `need_sync`
was being set using information from ansible_local in an effort to
support rolling uprades sometime in the future. Sadly this variable
causes storage nodes to be removed from the key sync which results in a
failed build.  The task to define the `need_sync` fact has been
commented out and noted. If we decide serialized rolling uprades are
required for swift we can revisit this however until then we need to
remove this constraint and ensure we're allowing successfule deployments
and upgrades of swift.

Change-Id: Ia8697285baa714ab345381b28574a222c5881954
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Use generic user for both zuul v2 and v3

Zuul v2 uses 'jenkins' as user, but Zuul v3 uses 'zuul'.
Using $USER solves it for both cases.

Change-Id: I42c3328bf7ce5dbb745eb21954bc5528a6befed5

commit_message:
Fix loading of tempest-conf.sh for Cinder LIO job

tempest-conf.sh does not exist at the point of this check
because Cinder has not yet been cloned.

Export the setting assuming that the file will be
present instead.

Change-Id: I2d6efb01dc8422a40d0631e10cd1a0d9f802087b

commit_message:
Make centos7-undercloud-upgrades job vote.

overcloud-upgrades jobs have been already voting for
some time while undercloud-upgrades haven't. We see
it's the moment to make it vote.

Depends-On: I558e86f5cec139cef165b0908bb3861434c7c8bc

Change-Id: Ib921f1b890d974f9dfe058b5f6116f979e4ac5be

commit_message:
Support  multiprocessing parallel evaluation of Vitrage templates.

Per event template matching runs in parallel,
using N EvaluatorWorkers each holding a copy of the graph,
and executing different templates.

Change-Id: I9d777fde1ea2bc3155c3eca8a30877aedd669081
Depends-On: I2d1e31e386a2576b3a44ec5b8e15dc49d2a474d3
Implements: blueprint parallel-evaluation

commit_message:
Fix theme rendering for kilo

Set WEBROOT in openstack-dashboard's local_settings.py to the value
of webroot from the charm's config (see config.yaml).

Add /horizon/static alias to apache2 config in addition to /static
to cover both paths to static resources.

Change-Id: I29a156d322bac91ca02fb0f08f291fc805e59110
Closes-Bug: #1728086

commit_message:
DNM Test fullstack test only with 1 worker

We want to check how long it would take for fullstack tests
to finish only with 1 worker.
As tests will work one by one it can be solution/workaround
e.g. for issue with race condition for processing trunk
ports and bridges by Openvswitch agents.

Depends-On: Ieb2b8916d4cdbb3b7e6a953c827b176f2217a42f
Depends-On: Ic01086dd596a80b461a5cc9884536c48468340e9

Change-Id: Icca6125d06225624be774521b58e715ad814eabf

[{'created': '2017-10-30 12:03:00.000000000', 'message': "Make charms.ceph fully py2/py3 compatible

These changes make the charms.ceph library suitable for both the
old-stable Python 2 charms and the (to be) updates Python 3 only charms.
Avoided use of six by using str() with the decode('UTF-8') function to
allow the library to be used with both Py2 and Py3.  The str(...)
coercions can be removed at a later date when the library no longer
needs to be synced to Py2 versions of the ceph-* charms.

Change-Id: I416053439444bf4cf8945d1fe96643f9ed0f05f4
"}]
commit_message:
Make charms.ceph fully py2/py3 compatible

These changes make the charms.ceph library suitable for both the
old-stable Python 2 charms and the (to be) updates Python 3 only charms.
Avoided use of six by using str() with the decode('UTF-8') function to
allow the library to be used with both Py2 and Py3.  The str(...)
coercions can be removed at a later date when the library no longer
needs to be synced to Py2 versions of the ceph-* charms.

Change-Id: I416053439444bf4cf8945d1fe96643f9ed0f05f4

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

commit_message:
Add a collector for Monasca

This adds a collector for Monasca. For now, only ceilometer metrics
published by ceilosca (https://github.com/openstack/monasca-ceilometer)
are collected, but this should be extended in the future.

Change-Id: If4553dd1ab1a45846699735979b54426e121a0b1
Task: 5717
Story: 2001211

commit_message:
Change parent to parent_name in lsp_add

Since **columns is accepted and the column name that 'parent'
refers to is actually 'parent_name', passing 'parent_name' in
**columns doesn't work. This changes the argument parent to match
the actual column name.

Change-Id: I2373015677c73a0da85bd44b3c5c117c3345302f

commit_message:
persist memcached logs in /var/log/containers/memcached/memcached.log

We used to bind-mount /var/log/memcached.log, but this resulted in the
file being createdin the memcached container as a directory, since this
file didn't exist.

This commit takes the approach of other containers and gets the logs to
a memcached directory in /var/log/containers.

Change-Id: I926b65fa557ad56b4faa2be34452b58f7b01247a
Closes-Bug: #1720183

commit_message:
Set verbosity by default for memcached

This sets of one level of verbosity for memcached by default. This
allows us to see any errors or warnings in the logs.

Change-Id: Icc6f56c9e0ee6100286d07c8b6660a08baabb241
Related-Bug: #1720183

[{'created': '2017-08-28 13:00:07.000000000', 'message': "DNM: try possible fix to missing config drive setting

The force_config_drive setting is apparently not making it's way into
the nova configuration. This change aligns with other service templates
that need to configure other services.

Change-Id: I595f89dbec86425d678978ab4e3528799dbdfebc
"}]
commit_message:
DNM: try possible fix to missing config drive setting

The force_config_drive setting is apparently not making it's way into
the nova configuration. This change aligns with other service templates
that need to configure other services.

Change-Id: I595f89dbec86425d678978ab4e3528799dbdfebc

'}, {'created': '2017-04-18 12:23:43.000000000', 'message': 'Deprecate DHCP providers

The DHCP providers are deprecated and will be removed in Queens release.

For those who using custom dhcp providers, custom network_interfaces
or custom deploy drivers. The network_interfaces should implement
`clean_dhcp` and `get_ip_addresses` methods. DHCP options are now set
when calling the following methods from network_interface and may be
passed as optional parameter `dhcp_opts`:

    * `add_provisioning_network`
    * `add_cleaning_network`
    * `configure_tenant_networks`

Closes-Bug: #1683777

Change-Id: I28960f499c0655f1e6c90044161bd88931912f79

commit_message:
Deprecate DHCP providers

The DHCP providers are deprecated and will be removed in Rocky release.

For those who using custom dhcp providers, custom network_interfaces
or custom deploy drivers. The network_interfaces should implement
`clean_dhcp` and `get_ip_addresses` methods. DHCP options are now set
when calling the following methods from network_interface and may be
passed as optional parameter `dhcp_opts`:

    * `add_provisioning_network`
    * `add_cleaning_network`
    * `configure_tenant_networks`

Closes-Bug: #1683777

Change-Id: I28960f499c0655f1e6c90044161bd88931912f79

commit_message:
use Newton sha's for cross repo versions

Newton has started removing the stable/newton branch across several
projects. To ensure we're not breaking the newton gate as we work
through the last few weeks of this release, this change modifies the
checkout versions of our pinned projects to use the latest stable SHA.

Change-Id: Ia3009901d63068b379f22d587efcba996f47b844
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Add image_member_quota to Glance API configuration

Allow the configuration of image_member_quota
in Glance API. This error blocks the ability
of sharing images if the default value (128)
is reached.

Change-Id: Id4bdf7f755f5b595ccd912f083d76bfdfac5bd06
Closes-bug: 1724879

commit_message:
Revert "Move log collection to 'post' stage"

This reverts commit fd4db8ea906d60a21b44205f796c769eeb51a764.
The playbook used here needs to be in every repo calling that job
(which is all our branches and all our repos).

I suggest we revert it until alll the other zuul v3 changes are settled.
We can then take a more organized approach.

Change-Id: I8ba967af69311fc0684635462d27cdc03728ca81

commit_message:
Switch to use keystone v3

Keystone v2 api's are removed in [1], so it's required
to use keystone v3 otherwise all requests fallbacks to
keystone v2.0 and fails.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/499783/

Change-Id: I0464d6b37c3e269d3bdc1eb5034ec751f977b6a8
Closes-Bug: #1723838

[{'created': '2017-10-25 13:21:48.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] [Qos] Fix cleaning of ingress bandwidth limit in ovs agent

When e.g. Nova deletes port with attached QoS policy, Neutron
calls QoS extension driver methods to delete QoS rules from this port.
In case if vif_port not exists anymore driver is just doing nothing.
This is fine for egress bandwidth limit as it is configured directly
on vif_port in OVS.
For ingress bw limit however it's uses additional records in Openvswitch
database: qos and queue. Those records wasn't cleaned in such case.

This patch changes id which is configured in "external_ids" of qos and
queue records from port_name to port_id.
Id of port is known even during port deletion and thanks to that
driver can clean such qos and queue records

Change-Id: Icdfe507c26c469e56492cbf03162c3ef9182eca7
Closes-Bug: #1726732
'}]
commit_message:
[WIP] [Qos] Fix cleaning of ingress bandwidth limit in ovs agent

When e.g. Nova deletes port with attached QoS policy, Neutron
calls QoS extension driver methods to delete QoS rules from this port.
In case if vif_port not exists anymore driver is just doing nothing.
This is fine for egress bandwidth limit as it is configured directly
on vif_port in OVS.
For ingress bw limit however it's uses additional records in Openvswitch
database: qos and queue. Those records wasn't cleaned in such case.

This patch changes id which is configured in "external_ids" of qos and
queue records from port_name to port_id.
Id of port is known even during port deletion and thanks to that
driver can clean such qos and queue records

Change-Id: Icdfe507c26c469e56492cbf03162c3ef9182eca7
Closes-Bug: #1726732

Previously we used a complex job definition to make sure
that the appropriate git clones for cross-repo testing
were in place. Now we just used the same location where
zuul v3 puts the git sources automatically when a
cross-repo test is done.

This ensures that our cross-repo tests do what they're
supposed to and that we're using the same default location
as the rest of openstack's tests, making it more intuitive.

Change-Id: Ia5ab6aa43f912b3cb4adf98154cd3da12688c2e0
"}]
commit_message:
Use new zuul v3 git src location

Previously we used a complex job definition to make sure
that the appropriate git clones for cross-repo testing
were in place. Now we just used the same location where
zuul v3 puts the git sources automatically when a
cross-repo test is done.

This ensures that our cross-repo tests do what they're
supposed to and that we're using the same default location
as the rest of openstack's tests, making it more intuitive.

Change-Id: Ia5ab6aa43f912b3cb4adf98154cd3da12688c2e0

----------------------------------------------------------------------

    content_type='json')
  File "glance/tests/utils.py", line 564, in get_api_response_ext
    self.assertEqual(res.status_int, http_resp)

    raise mismatch_error
testtools.matchers._impl.MismatchError: 200 != 204

in tox_siblings which is causing incorrect versions to be
installed.

commit_message:
Support Kubernetes as VIM in Tacker

This spec proposes supporting containerized VNF in Tacker using
Kubernetes as VIM.

By default, Tacker has only OpenStack as VIM. Kubernetes is one
platform to orchestration containers. This spec focuses on CRUD
Kubernetes VIM in Tacker.

blueprint: kubernetes-as-vim

Change-Id: I7fa57515a80a6f8a424cbf1c388ac025e308ec80
Co-Authored-By: Janki Chhatbar <jchhatba@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Trinath Somanchi <trinath.somanchi@nxp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Xuan Jia <jiaxuan@chinamobile.com>

[{'created': '2017-10-20 08:17:04.000000000', 'message': 'Remove check flat network type task in ironic pre-check.yml

flat network type is not mandatory. There are two cases,

1. ironic with flat network: we can use neutron vlan network to
   provision baremetal nodes, as long as the interface of the baremetal
   nodes are configured to use the same vlan.

2. ironic with neutron network: all provision and cleaning_network can
   be vlan type and no flat is needed at all.

commit_message:
Remove check flat network type task in ironic pre-check.yml

flat network type is not mandatory. There are two cases,

1. ironic with flat network: we can use neutron vlan network to
   provision baremetal nodes, as long as the interface of the baremetal
   nodes are configured to use the same vlan.

2. ironic with neutron network: all provision and cleaning_network can
   be vlan type and no flat is needed at all.

So we should remove the task.

Change-Id: I176ded6d2a8b14e350f665f63bc37eb488d32679
Closes-Bug: #1725170

(2 comments)

The jenkins/script directory is backed into our images, to use it you need to rebuild the images which happens daily.

So, in general: Before you can use anything written to jenkins/script, wait a day or two.

That's why we use jobs/jenkins/include - those scripts are inline and can be used directly.

So, rearrange the scripts..."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2017-07-11 12:36:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-07-11 12:49:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I like the idea of doing this, but I'm not sure this is the right implementation, for 2 reasons:

1. We are going to have to solve a similar problem for content in the doc/source directories for projects (installation guides, especially). 
2. The special releasenotes build job will go away when we merge it into doc/source and use the single unified job.

Do you think it would be possible to do something in the openstackdocstheme to add the necessary links?"}, {'account_id': 14482, 'date': '2017-07-17 00:32:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

It is a good idea to have more visibility on the language list for better I18n. I also agree with Doug that it can apply to openstackdocstheme and IMO the work would be fine but I cannot imagine how it affects on PDF generation now.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2017-07-19 09:05:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Investigate an approach in openstackdocstheme'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2017-10-29 14:10:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We have switched to Zuul v3 now, this change does not apply anymore.

Learn on how to update your change with Zuul v3 at
https://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/zuulv3.html .

Simplified:
* Job definitions can be in-repo; common job definitions are in
  openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs repository
* Job scheduling can be done in-repo for project specific changes,
  common jobs are configured via
  openstack-infra/project-config/zuul.d/projects.yaml

Read the above mentioned document for finer details.

Please decide whether this change is still needed and then adopt if
for Zuul v3 or abandon it.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2017-10-30 05:51:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

I know the zuulv3 migration and this no longer cannot be applied as-is.
I just keep this open for my note (with WIP), but I think I have no time to move this forward. I still believe the feature itself is useful and hope someone work on the feature.'}]

commit_message:
build-releasenotes: Add language index to all files

Release notes files are usually not accessed through index.html
and release notes of individual releases are accessed directly
as they are linked from releases.openstack.org.

It is better to have language list for all release notes files
so that readers can easily find translated versions.

Change-Id: If69520d3875941a51b194723ecfe524adf802cad

commit_message:
Fix gate / add tempest job

The Zuul v3 conversion missed the
tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-python-troveclient job and the base
tempest job is running in its place and blocking the gate.

This adds the Zuul project config and the definition for the
missing tempest job.

Change-Id: I532776e2e23b1ab5a5c9ef2b0278489f04a1097f

commit_message:
Added AddNetwork command to server

Currently, if users want to add another NIC to a running instance,
they need to (i) create a neutron port and (ii) add the port to the
server via teh AddPort command. It would be more convenient to have
a single command to achieve the equivalent.

Novaclient already support adding network to an instance via the
interface-attach command. This patch introduces a similar capability
in OSC.

Change-Id: Ia3e39c57ae7ecb96aae1b66adc52c289daccb6ec

Currently when we need a help, client object is created
and authentication is performed. This is completely useless
and leads to unnecessary actions in the background.

This patch:
1. Prevents creation of client object (and therefore
authentication) for help or bash-completion commands.
2. Removes a workaround from keystone auth module that disables

commit_message:
Don't create client for help and bash completion

Currently when we need a help, client object is created
and authentication is performed. This is completely useless
and leads to unnecessary actions in the background.

This patch:
1. Prevents creation of client object (and therefore
authentication) for help or bash-completion commands.
2. Removes a workaround from keystone auth module that disables
sending requests to the server if help or bash-completion
commands are executing.
3. Adds related unit tests.

Change-Id: Ia26d7f4e56f5ef3ae0ac5e94e8e77d1a78f8829e
Closes-bug: #1720795
(cherry picked from commit d9da161c16bc524d4e1d64f09fa2d857cbcf4537)

commit_message:
Remove dlrnapi report at the end of the run

Counting on just job success is not enough to report success to the dlrn
api.
We need to be sure images are uploaded before reporting, which needs to
be done elsewhere

Related-Bug: #1724093
Change-Id: I625395e590ea3db2e17abb27e021832dafe553fb

commit_message:
Switch to use keystone v3

Keystone v2 api's are removed in [1], so it's required
to use keystone v3 otherwise all requests fallbacks to
keystone v2.0 and fails.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/499783/

Change-Id: Ifdf1493a1adf3384c7ccba78c1ed7b7710f83d40
Closes-Bug: #1723838

commit_message:
Fail on curl error when setting up repo

If the repo raises an error, there is no reason to be silent, setup will
fail later on. Let's fail explicitely when curl is called.

Change-Id: Ief5b319082a90b45b912ae3efcfbe2d2e77906e0

commit_message:
EMC XtremIO driver does not honor create from snapshot volume size

In case the new volume from snapshot is larger than the created one,
resize the created volume.

Change-Id: Ia8ba3b6e44a4855fe728444dd3e9753391268a93
Closes-Bug: #1560650

commit_message:
Zuul: add file extension to playbook path

Zuul now supports including the file extension on the playbook path
and omitting the extension is now deprecrated.  Update references
to include the extension.

Change-Id: I6f1d939c9b44811fbbad3e67bebed56308d2e892

commit_message:
Remove tempest job

Remove the lib-forward-testing job to remove the regular
tempest test which does not enable the Trove plugin.

The job to run tempest with the Trove plugin enabled
and other projects pulled in is being added to the
python-troveclient repo under
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/515393/

Change-Id: Ic30939fb7d6ace9cb621c0a5c241dbbce80668d1

Update zuul-cloner dependencies for OpenStack-Helm projects

OpenStack-Helm-Addons repo hosting helm charts that have dependencies

support NFS as well as Ceph.

Add multinode stable branches jobs for quickstart, make them
experimental now for stability testing.

Change-Id: I27ab25ef0f2c74e4b06a713e2ba0071efc744181

Ideally this report can be run to see which projects are doing
the most docs and api-ref changes and reviews. Would be helpful
to see which projects need docs contributors, which projects
need docs reviewers, which projects have healthy docs.

- Help wanted: I'm not sure how to have the genresults script get info
  from the reviewstats/docstats.py file specifically?
- Ideally would also report the amount of time it takes to merge docs
  or api-ref changes.

commit_message:
Adds api-ref, docs, or installdocs statistics measures

Use --apiref or --docs or --installdocs as arguments to view docs stats.

Ideally this report can be run to see which projects are doing
the most docs and api-ref changes and reviews. Would be helpful
to see which projects need docs contributors, which projects
need docs reviewers, which projects have healthy docs.

Change-Id: Ifce720a3c796d4f0a7d3dc6383f9dfb4384f7220

commit_message:
Don't install bindep-fallbacks with recommends turned on

bindeps should be exactly installed like advertised with no additional
optional packages being implicitely installed as well. This makes
it consistent with installations on other distributions and reduces
the install overhead greatly.

Change-Id: Ib789e53979da5ab7142a7cd452335e1b31e47ebd

commit_message:
Remove default names for NB objects

Ports, networks, subnets, SGs, routers and FIPs had a Dragonflow
specific name in NB DB instance when Neutron objects lacked a name.
This patch removes this, so new objects will have similar name in both
DF's and Neutron databases.

Change-Id: I3b4b81fc0d2228ea937b234ef21abce06d83b814

commit_message:
update contributor internals index

A number of our RSTs under doc/srouce/contributor/internals/* are not
referenced from the index.rst and as a result are not
published/accessible in our docs.

This patch updates the index to ref all internal pages.

Change-Id: If534f8d6a7da2807285edb6885c800696d1c50a9
Closes-Bug: #1712907
(cherry picked from commit 2750590cde2c2fbf2b62a753966e77b1c0fa8c1d)

[{'account_id': 25320, 'date': '2017-10-27 09:42:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2017-10-27 09:42:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 24209, 'date': '2017-10-27 09:44:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 23419, 'date': '2017-10-27 09:50:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11975, 'date': '2017-10-27 14:49:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I don't have anything against such changes but is it really necessary and valuable?"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2017-10-28 15:14:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I am giving +2 only because this is post by a new contributor and it does not affect the existing code.

Precisely speaking, 'return' here in this pattern sometimes has the meaning to express the intention we would like to return immediately. In this case, there is no following logic in the method so it is clear, but this might be a result of refactoring on code. If so, it is not easy to detect this kind of things and we tend to accept them.

As a summary, I am okay to accept this as an exception. It is better to be fixed as part of related fixes if any and there is no need for a patch only to drop it. If the author proposes the similar one for neutron again, I definitely give -1."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2017-10-29 11:52:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}]

commit_message:
use availability zone api def from lib

Commit I1d4ded9959c05c65b04b118b1c31b8e6db652e67 rehomed the
availability zone extension's API definition into neutron-lib. This
patch consumes it, removing the rehomed logic in neutron and switching
over to lib's version of it.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I761381de0d6e26a0380386700e7921b824991669

commit_message:
Enable Cinder as a backend for Glance

Enable Cinder as a backend for Glance by adding 'cinder' to the list of
allowed choices for the GlanceBackend heat parameter.

Update the glance-api docker configuration to allow the feature to work.
This is necessary because the feature uses iSCSI, which requires additional
privileges.

Depends-On: I850047e32f3608b3ce490e52e2e540695cb1a4ff
Change-Id: I42241747de931103a04aa5ee2ed18fd46197d183

commit_message:
Adding end_msg_flag param to make_pickleable func.

Since vitrage support the creation of new drivers,
make_pickleable function can be used for various drivers,
including drivers which outside of openstack vitrage.
In order to enable drivers to use make_pickleable func
without adding end_message (use case example: pagination
purposes), end_msg_flag param is added.
The default value is set to True to ensure backward
compatibility.

Change-Id: I684b2dc9ee4b90fffc8b70fb0ddd7bbecd0504f1

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

The neutron_dhcp_config option was being set in vars which makes it
immutable. This option is set within our playbooks and needs to be
available to for override. To allow the neutron_dhcp_config option to be
overriden or extended it has been moved back to defaults.

Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Move the neutron_dhcp_config back to defaults

The neutron_dhcp_config option was being set in vars which makes it
immutable. This option is set within our playbooks and needs to be
available to for override. To allow the neutron_dhcp_config option to be
overriden or extended it has been moved back to defaults.

Change-Id: I30d4f676ffbbac5f1541c7e8fe188c10d8c6148e
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
use qos constants from neutron-lib

neutron-lib contains the QoS constants. This patch removes them from
neutron and replaces all such uses to lib's QoS constants.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I6ed379b178a2b79fd14385a1d1e87d87eb04bfb9

commit_message:
Rename base.rebuild_server to base.recreate_server

In https://review.openstack.org/#/c/503515/, compute.base.
rebuild_server will be renamed as recreate_server to
distinguish from servers_client.rebuild_server, so this
is to change the helper name in tempest plugin accordingly.

Depends-on: I1589750870dff1a2681192e2f3d151ef18bf4d2a
Change-Id: I142ef812ef56595e8b0c64f1c1d4fe52342ea791

commit_message:
Fix TypeError being raised by json.dumps in policy_authority

This PS also catches TypeError raised by json.dumps if the policy
data is malformed.

For example, right now in Cinder, a policy action defined in code
is mistakenly a tuple [0] (which is a bug [1]) causing json.dumps
to throw a TypeError because a key in the dict is a tuple rather
than a string.

[0] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/c6a82637fb777cec8df93ce02b2d65e8bb54c247/cinder/policies/capabilities.py#L21
[1] I1d924da3504861f027273d3319e5cf6c485d1d37

Change-Id: Idf05dc97a932cdbff2a336a91026d8104b0ec243
Depends-On: I1d924da3504861f027273d3319e5cf6c485d1d37

commit_message:
Use ksa adapter for placement conf & requests

Switch usage of the placement API over to using the new
nova.utils.get_ksa_adapter method.  Now REST calls with the placement
API go through the resulting keystoneauth1 Adapter - which already
incorporates endpoint filtering - rather than a keystoneauth1 Session.

To make this fit, switch the placement conf over to using
nova.conf.utils.register_ksa_opts and get_ksa_adapter_opts.  In so
doing, deprecate os_interface and os_region_name in favor of the
imported Adapter opts valid_interfaces and region_name, respectively.

Change-Id: I69e9b30d96390a70198b12d74e7efa9bd61db217
Partial-Implements: bp use-ksa-adapter-for-endpoints

commit_message:
Heat Fixes

- currently non-admin user aren't able to create stacks with i.e.
  Resource OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment
- added heat domain
        heat domain_admin
        heat_stack_owner and user role
- added missing configuration options
- version bumped
- updated Berksfile.lock
- increased metrics/blocklength
  identity_registration spec got new specs

commit_message:
Fix duplicate standalone_network_plugin_ip_version

in the generated sample configuration.  This option is deprecated
and should no longer have a ``deprecated_group`` setting.

So remove it.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: Ie24bab0f51d2bd1434593eb0d2f3b65b88904a78

commit_message:
[placement] Limit number of attempts to delete allocations

In _set_allocations a list of allocations is traversed. For each one, we
delete all the allocations for the consumer uuid in the allocation.
Since some of the allocations in the list can have the same consumer
uuid, make a set of those consumers and only delete once.

This is an optimization that will reduce the number of SQL statements
made by _set_allocations when it is used in forthcoming patches that
enable multiple allocation to be POSTed to /allocations.

Change-Id: Id742cc8b07bcb07fb59986c0643d0d0311be97de

to be reverted with commit c8628dd8f846567a3686e428324f4b29b8aa5ed4).

The original change had a small syntax error using
"zuul.projects.values()" instead of "zuul._projects.values()".  This
is corrected here.

It also had a problem with_items: zuul._projects.values() -- in
python3 this returns a view, which doesn't work with "with_items:"
... so you need to "| list".

Integration test results (for use-cached-repos at least) in
I7828f78efd1d20031cf1c34629200f265576e7a7.

Change-Id: I9d88f405f34d1c5f75ebf4f52cedfaaab20c3bda

commit_message:
Fix networking settings for ObjectStorage role

The role name is actually "ObjectStorage", not "SwiftStorage". This
leads do failing deployments if one or more ObjectStorage nodes are
deployed on the overcloud.

Closes-Bug: 1727475

commit_message:
revert base extension unit test param removal

Commit I2586f0b11b107d7f57214a0d65bcf7c38a5f0ebb changed the private
_setUpExtension() method in neutron/tests/unit/extensions/base.py by
removing a now unused parameter. However consumers are using the private
method so the resulting change breaks them in some cases.

This patch adds the param back as well as a todo to phase it out by
moving consumers off it 1st.

Closes-Bug: 1727988
Change-Id: I782e6d6fb6e575c00644f72602bc90a3d25bc18c

commit_message:
Add dbid parameter to pools's uri based on redis

Now based on redis stored message store, zaqar can only write data
into dbid = 0 database, it is not very convenient. Redis database has
default 16 dbid database instances. In the redis pool's uri,we
add dbid configuration parameters, if not dbid Parameter,
the default dbid = 0.

Change-Id: I6ba7b7ea0b0396ef56c920c1610552ece9779674

[{'created': '2017-10-26 21:57:56.000000000', 'message': "Add unit tests to check for CONF getattr during import

Since the early days in tempest we've been fighting getattrs on CONF
during imports. We're able to get around this during test runs by lazy
loading the conf file. However, in things like the tempest commands this
doesn't work because we rely on the config file not being parsed to set
the config file path. This commit adds unit tests to check the import
of the command files for getattrs on CONF. This should prevent future
regressions.

While not strictly necessary because of the lazy loading this also gives
a framework to potentially address the CONF getatrr on discovery. The
first revision of this patch includes the discovery test, for reference.
But we have 212 cases of getattr during import (which includes lots of
skip decorators) so it's unlikely to change any time soon.

Change-Id: Ib2c15dbd06ca810cc899258758cc8a297055fdf8
Closes-Bug: #1726357

commit_message:
Add unit tests to check for CONF getattr during import

Since the early days in tempest we've been fighting getattrs on CONF
during imports. We're able to get around this during test runs by lazy
loading the conf file. However, in things like the tempest commands this
doesn't work because we rely on the config file not being parsed to set
the config file path. This commit adds unit tests to check the import
of the command files for getattrs on CONF. This should prevent future
regressions.

While not strictly necessary because of the lazy loading this also gives
a framework to potentially address the CONF getatrr on discovery. The
first revision of this patch includes the discovery test, for reference.
But we have 212 cases of getattr during import (which includes lots of
skip decorators) so it's unlikely to change any time soon.

Change-Id: Ib2c15dbd06ca810cc899258758cc8a297055fdf8
Closes-Bug: #1726357

commit_message:
Only filter/weigh hosts once if scheduling a single instance

If we're only scheduling for a single instance, we don't need
filter and weigh hosts another time before picking alternates
because the single selected host for the single instance can't
be in the list of filtered/weighed alternates anyway.

This helps avoid an unnecessary performance penalty for finding
alternates when we just have a single instance - which is likely
the majority of cases.

Change-Id: Ie065c4e169db4e02fbfa8ccadb0af23d2784cab8

commit_message:
Have create_pending_row return the entry

This change is needed in order to be able to print the entry's ID to the
log once it's created, in order to have better debug-ability of the logs
(we'll be able to correlate entries better if we know the ID and not
only the object ID which can have multiple entries).

A follow up patch makes use of this ability.

Change-Id: I8eb82a5e5c0124c1eaf5fb3cbf32e12fd169e7ff
Related-Bug: #1713487

commit_message:
Fix extension unit test after neutron change

Neutron Change I2586f0b11b107d7f57214a0d65bcf7c38a5f0ebb changed the
signature of _setUpExtension.

This updates unit tests to follow this change.

Switch scenario004-containers to use ceph-ansible

Use ceph-ansible to match the non-containerized variant of
scenario004.

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-26 22:44:07.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Don't disregard cache mode for instance boot disks

One of the things this commit:

    commit 14c38ac0f253036da79f9d07aedf7dfd5778fde8
    Author: Kashyap Chamarthy <kchamart@redhat.com>
    Date:   Thu Jul 20 19:01:23 2017 +0200

        libvirt: Post-migration, set cache value for Cinder volume(s)

    [...]

did was to supposedly remove "duplicate" calls to _set_cache_mode().

But that came back to bite us.

Now, while the Cinder volumes are taken care of w.r.t handling its cache
value during migration, but the above referred commit (14c38ac) seemed
to introduce a regression because it disregards the 'disk_cachemodes'
Nova config parameter altogether for boot disks -- i.e. even though if
a user set the cache mode to be 'writeback', it's ignored and
instead 'none' is set unconditionally.

Add the _set_cache_mode() calls back in _get_guest_storage_config().

Co-Authored-By: melanie witt <melwittt@gmail.com>

Closes-Bug: #1727558

 Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py

NOTE(melwitt): The conflict is from unit tests in pike that don't exist
in ocata.

Change-Id: I7370cc2942a6c8c51ab5355b50a9e5666cca042e
(cherry picked from commit 24e79bcbf7790d1f4fea2cbdf066599cc746c2dc)
(cherry picked from commit 60d6e87cac10ff1f95a028c6176e768214ec8b77)
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: Don't disregard cache mode for instance boot disks

One of the things this commit:

    commit 14c38ac0f253036da79f9d07aedf7dfd5778fde8
    Author: Kashyap Chamarthy <kchamart@redhat.com>
    Date:   Thu Jul 20 19:01:23 2017 +0200

        libvirt: Post-migration, set cache value for Cinder volume(s)

    [...]

did was to supposedly remove "duplicate" calls to _set_cache_mode().

But that came back to bite us.

Now, while the Cinder volumes are taken care of w.r.t handling its cache
value during migration, but the above referred commit (14c38ac) seemed
to introduce a regression because it disregards the 'disk_cachemodes'
Nova config parameter altogether for boot disks -- i.e. even though if
a user set the cache mode to be 'writeback', it's ignored and
instead 'none' is set unconditionally.

Add the _set_cache_mode() calls back in _get_guest_storage_config().

Co-Authored-By: melanie witt <melwittt@gmail.com>

Closes-Bug: #1727558

 Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py

NOTE(melwitt): The conflict is from unit tests in pike that don't exist
in ocata.

Change-Id: I7370cc2942a6c8c51ab5355b50a9e5666cca042e
(cherry picked from commit 24e79bcbf7790d1f4fea2cbdf066599cc746c2dc)
(cherry picked from commit 60d6e87cac10ff1f95a028c6176e768214ec8b77)
